SAS Functions and CALL Routines

  • A function is a component of the SAS programming language that can accept arguments, perform a computation or other operation, and return a value.

  • A CALL routine alters variable values or performs other system functions. CALL routines are similar to functions, but differ from functions in that you cannot use them in assignment statements or expressions.

Syntax of Functions and CALL Routines

  • function-name (argument-1<, ...argument-n>)
  • function-name (OF variable-list)
  • function-name (<argument | OF variable-list | OF array-name[*]>)

Function arguments

  • constants, abs(-1)
  • variables, int(cash)
  • expressions, min((enroll-drop),(enroll-fail))
  • other functions, left(upcase(City))

Variable-list

  • numbered range lists, sum(of y1-y10)
  • name range lists, studid--usubjid
  • Name Prefix Lists, sum(of Sales:)
  • Special SAS Name Lists
    • _NUMERIC_, all numeric variables that are already defined in the current DATA step
    • _CHARACTER_, all character variables that are already defined in the current DATA step
    • _ALL_, all variables that are already defined in the current DATA step cmiss(of _ALL_)=0

Function type

Functions and Procedures

Functions in DATA STEP row-wise operations

data class;
    set sashelp.class;
    mean_of_height_weight = mean(height, weight);;
run;

Procedures column-wise operations

proc means data=sashelp.class mean;
    var height;
run;

Functions in PROC SQL

proc sql;
    select mean(height) as mean_of_height
    from sashelp.class;
quit; 

proc sql;
    select height, weight, mean(height,weight) as mean_of_height_weight
    from sashelp.class
    ;
quit;

Character Functions

RANK and BYTE

  • RANK: Returns the position of a character in the ASCII collating sequence

      data _null_
      n=rank('A');
      put n;
  run;
  /* n = 65 */

  • BYTE: Returns one character in the ASCII collating sequence

      data _null_;
      x=byte(80);
      put x;
  run;
  /* x = P */

  • Check special characters

Concatenating Strings

  • Concatenation operator (either || or !!): not remove blanks and the length

  • CAT() functions: stripping leading and trailing spaces and converting numbers to characters

/*
newString = trim(left(string1)) || left(string2)
newString = cats(string1, string2)

newString = trim(left(string1)) || left(put(number, 10.));
newString = cats(string1, number);
*/
  • Concatenating Strings with a Delimiter
/*
newString = trim(left(string1)) || " " || left(string2);
newString = catx(" ", string1, string2);
*/

/* CATX() only puts the delimiter between non-blank values */
data test;
    string1 = " ";
    string2 = "A";
    string3 = "";
    string4 = "B";
    newString1 = string1 || "," ||string2 ||","|| string3 ||","||string4;
    newString2 = catx(",", of string:); /* variable list */
    newString3 = catx(",", of _all_); 
run;

Removing Leading and Trailing Spaces

  • LEFT: removes leading blanks
  • TRIM: removes the trailing blanks
  • TRIMN: removes trailing blanks from character expressions and returns a string with a length of zero if the expression is missing.
  • STRIP: removes all leading and trailing blanks and returns a string with a length of zero on a blank string

Finding Non-Blank Values

Character cases

  • LOWCASE: converts all characters of a string to lowercase
  • UPCASE: converts all characters of a string to uppercase
  • PROPCASE: converts the string to proper case, capitalize the first letter of each word
  • ANYLOWER: returns the position of the first lowercase character of a string
  • NOTLOWER: returns the position of the first not lowercase character of a string
  • ANYUPPER: returns the position of the first uppercase character of a string
  • NOTUPPER: returns the position of the first not uppercase character of a string
data test;
    string="this iS a string";
    lower_case = lowcase(string);
    upper_case = upcase(string);
    proper_case = propcase(string);
    any_lower = anylower(string);
    not_lower = notlower(string);
    any_upper = anyupper(string);
    not_upper = notupper(string);
run;
